abstract: WILMINGTON, N.C., Aug. 8.--Returns received during the past two days leave the result of the election still in doubt. Both parties claim a majority of the delegates, and it may be several days before the result is definitely known, as several extreme western counties are yet to be heard from. It is not probable that the majority will exceed two either way.

abstract: On Sunday evening Mr. Margaret Berg. of No.118 Seventh street, while walking through East Forty-eighth street, was robbed of a gold chain and locket by two young highwaymen. The prisoners were identified by Mrs. Berg, and Justice Kasmire, sitting at the Yorkville Police Court, committed them for trial in default of $2,000 bail each.

abstract: This has been another gloomy day for Saratoga. It began raining at daylight this morning and continued throughout the day, making people feel homesick and dejected. As the day grew older the storm increased in violence and the streets were turned into miniature rivers. Now and then it would lighten up and the visitors would hug the delusion that it was about to clear up, but the water only poured down in increased volume.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Aug. 26 1 A.M. Rains have prevailed near the Gulf Coast and in the North-west and clear or fair weather in the remaining districts, with eastealy to southerly winds and failing barometer. The temperature has risen slightly in all the districts. The barometer is highest in New-England, and decidedly low in the extreme North-west. The Ohio River has fallen slowly. The Mississippi has fallen slowly, except at Vicksburg, where it is reported rising.

abstract: PLYMOUTH, England, Aug. 27. After ten hours' deliberation to-day, the jury holding an inquest into the collision of the royal yacht with the yacht Mistletoe, were unable to agree. The work on the tunnel of the Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad Company under Jersey City Heights is being pushed forward with remarkable rapidity, considering the extent of the work and the many obstacles met with. In the construction of the great Hoosac Tunnel, which necessitated an outlay of many millions of dollars, the engineers met with many difficulties, but they found about as much soft as hard rock, but in the Delaware and Lackawanna Tunnel there is nothingbut solid trap rock.
